Step 1: Data cleaning

The process and code for data cleaning are meticulously documented within the data_cleaning.rmd / data_cleaning.ipynb files within the code directory. The executed data cleaning process was designed to align the data with the seven distinct dimensions of data quality, as delineated below:

  • Completeness - Reflects the extent to which all records possess anticipated data.
  • Uniqueness - Pertains to the degree of non-duplication among records within the dataset.
  • Timeliness - Conveys the degree of dataâ€™s currency and up-to-dateness.
  • Validity - Quantifies the extent to which dataset records conform to valid data types.
  • Accuracy - Measures dataâ€™s correctness and its fidelity in representing the truth.
  • Consistency - Defines the allowable deviation between two datasets.
  • Relevance - Gauges the dataâ€™s appropriateness for the required analysis.

This observation suggests that the preceding steps effectively addressed most of the violations. After each cleaning iteration, quality control checks were exerted to ensure compliance. Question 6. For individuals with both a pre and post response, compare the individual average change between the pre and post survey for each of Q1-4. Quantify the individual average change and report whether the difference between means is statistically significant.


The purpose of this analysis is to compare the average change between the pre and post survey for Q1 to Q4 and test weather that change is significant. The dataset used for this analysis is the combined, cleaned, unduplicated pre and post dataset.

To test for significance, I used the Wilcoxon signed-rank test.

The Wilcoxon signed-rank test is a non-parametric statistical test that is appropriate for comparing paired data when the distribution of the data may not be normal or when the assumptions of parametric tests like the t-test are not met. In this case, we are comparing the individual average change between the pre and post surveys for each question (Q1-4). Here are the reasons why I chose Wilcoxon signed-rank test as a suitable choice:

  • Paired Data: The Wilcoxon signed-rank test is designed for paired data, where each individual has two related measurements (pre and post survey).
  • Non-Normal Distribution: Data is not normally distributed (non-parametric).
  • Ordinal Data: Our data has ordinal response categories (Likert scale), the Wilcoxon test is appropriate because it does not require interval-level data.
  • Sensitive to Shifts: The Wilcoxon signed-rank test is sensitive to detecting shifts in the distribution, making it suitable for detecting changes in responses.

The wilcoxon signed-rank test is found in R under the stats library.
The results of the analysis and test are shown below.

| mean_change_Q1 | mean_change_Q2 | mean_change_Q3 | mean_change_Q4 | wilcox_Q1_p-val | wilcox_Q2_p-val | wilcox_Q3_p-val | wilcox_Q4_p-val |
|:---------------|:---------------|:---------------|:---------------|:----------------|:----------------|:----------------|:----------------|
| 0.07053763     | 0.2305376      | 0.1221505      | 0.3195699      | 0.001272983     | 3.802891e-23    | 2.457798e-08    | 1.39444e-45     |


Observations

In the aggregate analysis, statistically significant distinctions emerge in the average change in responses for each question between the pre and post surveys. The notably diminutive p-values underscore the improbability of these disparities arising by random variability, signifying substantial shifts in responses.

Specifically, a notable positive and statistically significant change in mean participantsâ€™ responses is observed across all four questions (Q1, Q2, Q3, and Q4) between the pre and post surveys. Among these, Q4 registers the most pronounced alteration in responses, accompanied by the lowest p-value, emphasizing both the substantiality of the observed change and its statistical significance.
